<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Thursday.</em></p><table class=3D"header=
" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Payment for order flow, etc.</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know. The basic situat=
ion is:=C2=A0</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px;=
 margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Retail investors in =
US stock markets get to trade for free and get really good execution on the=
ir stock trades.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Everybody is mad =
about it.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Retail investors get free t=
rades because wholesale market makers pay retail brokers for the privilege =
of trading with their customers=E2=80=99 orders, which=C2=A0means that the =
retail brokers can make lots of money without charging commissions. They ge=
t good execution because (1) it is very pleasant for those market makers to=
 trade with retail orders,=C2=A0which are less dangerous, less likely to su=
ffer from adverse selection, than institutional orders on the stock exchang=
e, and (2) the market makers=C2=A0<em>compete=C2=A0</em>with each other to =
execute those orders efficiently, and if they do not give retail orders goo=
d execution then the retail brokers will send the orders to other market ma=
kers. I am not going to rehash this in detail because nobody ever changes t=
heir mind, but I have written about it extensively <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27976693.262609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ=
2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYwNzIyX01PTkVZ=
U1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjI=
wNjA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea2f4338" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> here</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everybody is mad about it =
because it=C2=A0<em>seems=C2=A0</em>fishy. Surely if market makers are payi=
ng retail brokers for order flow it is because they are up to no good. The =
market makers seem to be getting pretty rich, while the retail traders ofte=
n =E2=80=A6=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t. And certainly it seems like a conflict of =
interest: If the retail brokers are getting paid to send their orders to ma=
rket makers, how can you trust that they=E2=80=99re doing the right thing f=
or the retail orders?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So now <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27976693.262609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
d3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zZWMtY2xvc2VzLWluLW9uLXJ1bGVzLXRoYXQtY291bGQtcmVzaGF=
wZS1ob3ctc3RvY2stbWFya2V0LW9wZXJhdGVzLTExNjU0NTQ0Nzk5P21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PX=
lhaG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf3318b68" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">everything is going to b=
e different</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities=
 and Exchange Commission is preparing to propose major changes to the stock=
 market=E2=80=99s plumbing as soon as this fall.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Chairman Gary Gensler directed SEC staff last year to explore ways to=
 make the stock market more efficient for small investors and public compan=
ies. While aspects of the effort are in varying stages of development, one =
idea that has gained traction is to require brokerages to send most individ=
ual investors=E2=80=99 orders to be routed into auctions where trading firm=
s compete to execute them, people familiar with the matter said. =E2=80=A6<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most consequential change being discuss=
ed would affect the way trades are handled after an investor places a so-ca=
lled market order with a broker to buy or sell a stock. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Unde=
r the auctions being considered by the SEC, different firms would compete w=
ith each other to fill an individual investor=E2=80=99s trade, according to=
 people familiar with the agency=E2=80=99s plans. Such a mechanism would fu=
ndamentally alter the business model of wholesalers, which can make more mo=
ney by trading against small investors than they do on public exchanges, wh=
ere they might find themselves trading with other sophisticated trading fir=
ms or institutional investors.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Will this be good for retail execution? The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/27976693.262609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMDYvc2VjLXdlaWdocy1zZW5kaW5nLXJldGFpbC1zdG9=
jay1vcmRlcnMtdG8tYXVjdGlvbnMtZm9yLWV4ZWN1dGlvbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjA3MjJfTU9ORV=
lTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yM=
jA2MDcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB149fd92f" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> wholesalers say no</a>, though they would:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Doug Cifu, Virtu=E2=80=99s chief executive officer, sa=
id the SEC should be careful not to make changes that unintentionally make =
trading more expensive. =E2=80=9COrder-by-order competition enables selecti=
ve competition because it removes the retail brokers=E2=80=99 ability to de=
mand best execution from wholesalers on every order,=E2=80=9D he said in a =
statement.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe current marke=
t structure has resulted in tighter spreads, greater transparency, and mean=
ingfully reduced costs,=E2=80=9D a spokesperson for Citadel Securities said=
 in an emailed statement. =E2=80=9CWe look forward to reviewing the proposa=
ls and working with the SEC and the industry towards our longstanding objec=
tive of further improving competition and transparency.=E2=80=9D</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And nobody exactly says yes. And yet eve=
ryone=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>mad about the current system, so I suppose scra=
pping it and starting over is a political winner.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Also the potential bad outcome here is that retail investors will ge=
t worse execution or won=E2=80=99t be able to trade for free, and I am not =
sure that the SEC would=C2=A0<em>mind=C2=A0</em>that. =E2=80=9CThe SEC <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27976693.262609/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zZWMtY2xvc2VzLWluLW9uLXJ1bGVzLXRoYXQtY291b=
GQtcmVzaGFwZS1ob3ctc3RvY2stbWFya2V0LW9wZXJhdGVzLTExNjU0NTQ0Nzk5P21vZD1pdHBf=
d3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCf3318b68" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">commenced its r=
eview</a> of market structure after the frenzied trading in GameStop Corp. =
and other meme stocks in early 2021 brought fresh scrutiny to the handling =
of individual investors=E2=80=99 trades,=E2=80=9D and honestly it would be =
very weird if a securities regulator=E2=80=99s main takeaway from GameStop =
was =E2=80=9Cwe need to improve the execution quality of retail stock order=
s.=E2=80=9D The problem with GameStop, to a regulator, was not that=C2=A0<e=
m>spreads on retail GameStop orders were too wide</em>; it was that too man=
y people were buying GameStop at seemingly irrational prices. One could ima=
gine the SEC wanting to rewrite the rules to <em>add=C2=A0</em>frictions to=
 retail trading, for instance, by=C2=A0restructuring the payment-for-order-=
flow model to make it harder to offer commission-free retail trading. If th=
e retail trading experience got a bit worse, there might be a bit less reta=
il trading, and deep down that might be what the SEC wants.</p><table class=
