on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">article about Tiger =
Global Management</a>, which became famous in the most recent tech boom for=
 disaggregating this bundle. Tiger Global certainly raised money:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2021, as some veteran venture capital=
ists warned that valuations in the sector were unsustainable, Tiger sought =
$10 billion for a fund, extolling the virtues of fast-growing software comp=
anies to potential investors. It finalized the fund in March 2022 with $12.=
7 billion in commitments. The firm neared $100 billion in assets under mana=
gement, an internal goal of some Tiger executives, people familiar with the=
 firm said. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Privately, some of Tiger=E2=80=99s investors hav=
e grumbled about the rapid clip at which the firm was raising successive ve=
nture funds.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And it certainly =
convinced companies to take the money, in part by giving it to them quickly=
 and in large quantities:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ali J=
avid, chief executive of Wrapbook, an entertainment-industry software compa=
ny he co-founded in 2018, set out to raise Series B funding=E2=80=94an earl=
y round of funding=E2=80=94in October. He emailed a Tiger partner, who quic=
kly asked to speak the next morning at 8:30. When they spoke, =E2=80=9CHe h=
ad already gone through our entire Series B deck,=E2=80=9D Mr. Javid said, =
referring to his fundraising presentation. =E2=80=9CThree hours later, I go=
t a term sheet for $100 million.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
he deal valued the company at $1 billion, up from about $150 million in a f=
unding round seven months earlier, according to PitchBook. =E2=80=9CTiger o=
ffered us fuel and freedom to execute,=E2=80=9D Mr. Javid said.</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it got rid of =E2=80=94=C2=A0or outso=
urced =E2=80=94=C2=A0the part of the business where VC funds try to make th=
eir portfolio companies better:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Some startup founders said Tiger instead tells them its goal is to stay ou=
t of the way. If a company wants connections, Tiger can make them. If found=
ers want research, Tiger will commission consultants for them. But Tiger=E2=
=80=99s main offering is money, the founders said: It comes quickly and typ=
ically without new strings attached.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">And it at least de-emphasized the part where VC funds try to pick th=
e good companies:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Other venture=
 investors call it an index-fund-like approach to venture capital=E2=80=94m=
aking it vulnerable to a sector-wide chill. While traditional firms concent=
rate their bets hoping for one or two winners to drive their returns, Tiger=
 spreads bets broadly, sometimes backing competitors.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, to the extent it=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>try to=
 pick the good companies, it outsourced a lot of that work too:</p><blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tiger outsources much of its background re=
search to consultant Bain &amp; Co., where analysts interview customers and=
 create dossiers on prospective companies. Some founders said they were ama=
